<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
5. 
<taxonomicName LSID="AAF35167-2E59-537B-9125-4AAEB842E6B0" authority="Chodat, Bull. Herb. Boissier, ser. 2, 3: 419 (1903)." authorityName="Chodat, Bull. Herb. Boissier, ser. 2, 3: 419" authorityYear="1903" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. sulcicaulis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="sulcicaulis">M. sulcicaulis Chodat, Bull. Herb. Boissier, ser. 2, 3: 419 (1903).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="lectotype">
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lectotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
(designated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" author="Nowicke, WH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="294 - 364" refId="B37" refString="Nowicke, WH, 1968. Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 55 (3): 294 - 364, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" title="Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" volume="55" year="1968">Nowicke 1968</bibRefCitation>
: 351, first-step lectotype; Sennikov &amp; Sukhorukov, second-step lectotype designated here): PARAGUAY. In regione fluminis Tapiraguay, Aug.[ust] [without year], 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. Hassler 4328</emphasis>
(K000601203! isolectotypes B! G! P00743937! P00634433!). Note: This species was synonymized with 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="celosioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">M. celosioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchioretto, MS" journalOrPublisher="Pesquisas Botanica" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="5 - 51" refId="B31" refString="Marchioretto, MS, de Siqueira, JC, 1998. O genero Microtea Sw. (Phytolaccaceae) no Brasil. Pesquisas Botanica 48: 5 - 51" title="O genero Microtea Sw. (Phytolaccaceae) no Brasil." volume="48" year="1998">Marchioretto and de Siqueira (1998</bibRefCitation>
, sub 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="paniculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">M. paniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). We reinstate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chodat, Bull. Herb. Boissier, ser. 2, 3: 419" authorityYear="1903" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. sulcicaulis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="sulcicaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">M. sulcicaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to specific rank due to (1) strongly perennial life history, (2) stiff (not spreading) inflorescences, (3) larger fruit diameter, (4) alveolate seed surface (in 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="celosioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">M. celosioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is rough but without alveolae), and (5) predominant distribution in subtropical South America (Paraguay, South Brazil, and SE Bolivia).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Description.</emphasis>
Perennial herb with a taproot; stems up to 60 cm, sparsely branched, glabrous; rosulate leaves at least partially persistent, appressed to the stem, lanceolate to narrowly oblong, 3.0-8.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1.0 cm, tapering into the short petiole; cauline leaves numerous, continuously decreasing in size towards the inflorescence, sessile; inflorescence a spike, branched, with lateral shoots directed upwards and not spreading or whip-like; pedicels up to 0.5 mm, flowers with a bract and two bracteoles; perianth segments 5, greenish with white margin or yellowish, ovoid; stamens 5-8; stigmas 2, thick; fruit 1.5-2.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.30-1.50 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Fruits and seeds of Microtea sulcicaulis and M. bahiensis: A, B fruit of M. sulcicaulis, enclosed in the perianth (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) C, D seed of M. sulcicaulis (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) E, F fruit of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA) G, H seed of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255659" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">6A</figureCitation>
); pericarp readily scraped off the seed, with small finger-shaped outgrowths up to 0.3 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Fruits and seeds of Microtea sulcicaulis and M. bahiensis: A, B fruit of M. sulcicaulis, enclosed in the perianth (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) C, D seed of M. sulcicaulis (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) E, F fruit of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA) G, H seed of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255659" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">6B</figureCitation>
); seed 1.3-1.5 mm, with alveolate surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Fruits and seeds of Microtea sulcicaulis and M. bahiensis: A, B fruit of M. sulcicaulis, enclosed in the perianth (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) C, D seed of M. sulcicaulis (Paraguay, Caazapa Dept., Tavai, 7 Dec 1988, F. Mereles 2122, G) E, F fruit of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA) G, H seed of M. bahiensis (Brazil, Bahia state, Salvador, Dunas de Itapua, nr Hotel Stella Maris, N from Condominio Alamedas da Praia, 8 Jun 1993, P. de Queiroz 3211, PACA). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255659" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">6D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Rocky and sandy substrates at altitudes up to 1500 m a.s.l.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
